liberals, who favour even deeper integration into the global economy, against neo-mercantilists, who call for a relatively selective approach to globalization and the return to more interventionist industrial policies. Both sides claim to have the facts on their side.Inspired by the work of economists Ha-Joon Chang and Dani Rodrik, editors Andrew Smith and Dimitry Anastakis bring together essays from both historians and economists in this collection to test claims that wealth comes from either protectionism or free trade.With empirical research that spans more than a century of Canadian history, Smart Globalization demonstrates that Canada’s success stemmed neither from complete openness to globalization or policies of isolation and self-sufficiency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBusiness enterprisesxHistoryxCanada. 0aBusiness enterpriseszCanadaxHistory. 0aGlobalizationxHistoryxCanada. 0aGlobalizationzCanadaxHistory. 0aIndustriesxHistoryxCanada. 0aIndustrieszCanadaxHistory. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / International / General.2bisacsh1 aAnastakis, Dimitry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aAnastakis, Dimitry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBellamy, Matthew J ., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDilley, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmery, J .C. Herbert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinton, Michael N.A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuhlberg, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatteo, Livio Di, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMordue, Greig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb